narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: Yes. Great opportunity to take a deeper and more nuanced look into a significant topic that is overlooked by most other courses here. At the very least, it's worth taking the course for Shapiro.
Yes--amazing syllabus, and a privilege to work with a scholar such as Shapiro.
Prof. Shapiro has a brilliant mind -- don't miss this opportunity.

The class covers an interesting approach in political theory that tries to build on non-domination to break through sterile positive/negative liberty debates and flesh out a more coherent vision for the role of the state. The reading list is good and varied. Professor Shapiro is intimately familiar with the works and does a good job presenting and balancing criticism of them. At times, the discussion became a little listless, and it helps to come in with some of your own energy for the material.

I would recommend this course with a few reservations. I feel that class discussion was sometimes poor because of low participation. However, in another year the class could be much stronger and make for a great experience.
